{{Infobox person | name = Aaron of Neustadt | image = | alt = | caption = | other_names = | occupation = Austrian Talmudis | death_date = {{death-date|13 March 1421|df=yes}} | birth_place = | death_place = Vienna }}
'''Aaron of Neustadt''' was an Austrian Talmudist who with [[Shallum]] and [[Jaekel (Talmudic scholar)|Jaekel]] of Vienna formed a triumvirate of Talmudic scholars in Austria at the end of the fourteenth and beginning of the fifteenth century; uncle and chief instructor of [[Isserlein]], who frequently alludes in his works to the decisions and opinions of his teacher. [[Jacob Mölln]] (Maharil) also refers to him and his colleagues. Aaron suffered the death of a martyr, at Vienna, on 13 March 1421. He wrote a digest, "Hilkot Niddah," which is mentioned by Isserlein. A collection of sermons by Aaron is now known only through three citations in the works of Jacob Mölln and of Isserlein.
