{{short description|Collie owned by Calvin Coolidge}} {{good article}} {{Infobox animal |name = Rob Roy |image = Rob Roy (dog).jpg |image_size = |caption = |othername = |gender = Male |birth_date = c. 1922 |birth_place = [[Oshkosh, Wisconsin]] |death_date = {{death year and age|1928|1922}} |death_place = [[Washington, D.C.]] |species = ''[[Canis lupus familiaris]]'' |breed = [[collie]] |nationality = American |occupation = [[Companion animal]] |owner = [[Calvin Coolidge]] |appearance = White }} '''Rob Roy''' (1922–1928) was a white male [[collie]] owned by [[Calvin Coolidge]]. Coolidge's favorite pet, he was acquired by [[Grace Coolidge]] in 1922 after she became enamored with collies, having seen one of the breed perform in a circus. He later lived with the family in the White House.
Rob Roy was immortalized in a [[Howard Chandler Christy]] portrait of Grace Coolidge. He died in 1928 after a short illness.
==Life and death== [[File:Grace Coolidge Official portrait.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.6|The Christy portrait of Rob Roy and Grace Coolidge]] Rob Roy was acquired by Calvin Coolidge's wife, Grace Coolidge, in 1922 from Island White Kennels in [[Oshkosh, Wisconsin]].<ref name="bard">{{cite journal|last1=Bard|first1=Constance|title=Collies at Astolat|journal=Dog Fancier|date=1933|volume=42|page=21}}</ref> Grace Coolidge had reportedly become enthralled by collies after seeing one of the breed perform in a circus. During the period in which the Coolidges owned Rob Roy, they also had a female collie named Prudence Prim.<ref name="ruth">{{cite book|last1=Feldman|first1=Ruth|title=Calvin Coolidge|date=2005|publisher=Twenty-First Century Books|isbn=0822514966|page=92|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4q1qHFpm7iYC&dq=%22rob+roy%22+coolidge&source=gbs_navlinks_s}}</ref> In 1928 Rob Roy became ill and was unsuccessfully treated at [[Walter Reed Army Medical Center]], where he died.<ref name="bard"/> Upon his death Coolidge wistfully remarked,<ref name=natcity/>
{{quote|His especial delight was to ride with me in the boats when I went fishing. So although I know he would bark for joy as the grim boatman ferried him across the dark waters of the [[Styx]], yet his going left me lonely on the hither shore.}}
==Mannerisms== Rob Roy was known as Coolidge's "favorite" among a menagerie of pets he kept that included dogs, birds, cats, and [[raccoon]]s.<ref name="ruth"/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Otfinoski|first1=Steve|title=Calvin Coolidge|date=2008|publisher=Marshall Cavendish|isbn=0761428364|page=65}}</ref> Coolidge himself described Rob Roy as a "stately gentleman of great courage and fidelity".<ref name=natcity>{{cite book|last1=Lewis|first1=Tom|title=Washington: A History of Our National City|date=2015|publisher=Basic Books|isbn=0465039219|page=305|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-5JcCgAAQBAJ&dq=%22rob+roy%22+coolidge&source=gbs_navlinks_s}}</ref> Rob Roy was known to lead Coolidge to the [[Oval Office]] each morning in a stoic manner with gaze fixed forward.<ref name="truman"/> Rob Roy's stately characteristics aside, Coolidge frequently tried to trick the dog into chasing animals that appeared on screen during the showing of films at the [[White House]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Whitcomb|first1=John|title=Real Life at the White House|date=2002|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=0415939518|page=278|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p1unoHtahSsC&dq=%22rob+roy%22+coolidge&source=gbs_navlinks_s}}</ref> According to [[Harry Truman]], Coolidge once ordered [[United States Senator|Senator]] [[Morris Sheppard]] to surrender his sausage to the dog while Coolidge and Sheppard were having breakfast.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Klara|first1=Robert|title=The Hidden White House: Harry Truman and the Reconstruction of America's Most Famous Residence|date=2013|publisher=Macmillan|isbn=1250022932|page=260|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6VdLQkUoCSAC&dq}}</ref>
==Legacy== A portrait of Grace Coolidge by the American artist and illustrator Howard Chandler Christy that was hung in the [[Red Room (White House)|Red Room]] of the White House shows the First Lady with Rob Roy.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Harris|first1=Bill|title=The First Ladies Fact Book|date=2012|publisher=Leventhal|isbn=1579128912|page=458|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q8daE8a_KAoC&dq}}</ref> The dog's pose &ndash; a gaze directed toward Grace Coolidge &ndash; was achieved by feeding it candy from Coolidge's hand throughout the portrait sittings.<ref name="truman">{{cite book|last1=Truman|first1=Margaret|title=The President's House: 1800 to the Present|date=2007|publisher=Random House|isbn=030741731X}}</ref> The life-size painting is featured in the White House [[China Room]].<ref>{{cite web|title=China Room|url=http://www.whitehousemuseum.org/floor0/china-room.htm|website=www.whitehousemuseum.org|accessdate=16 May 2018}}</ref>
